  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is it OK if I copy-paste code while solving competitive programming problems?",
  "response": "Copy-pasting code in competitive programming can be a double-edged sword. Here are some considerations to help you decide whether it\u2019s appropriate:\n\n### When It\u2019s OK:\n1. **Boilerplate Code**:\n   - If you\u2019re copying standard template code (e.g., input/output handling, prewritten functions, or libraries), it\u2019s generally acceptable. Many competitive programmers use prewritten templates to save time.\n\n2. **Well-Known Algorithms**:\n   - For widely known algorithms (e.g., Dijkstra\u2019s, binary search, or Union-Find), copying from a trusted source is fine, especially if you\u2019ve implemented it yourself before and understand it.\n\n3. **Time Constraints**:\n   - In timed competitions, efficiency is key. If copying a snippet saves time and helps you focus on solving the problem, it\u2019s reasonable.\n\n4. **Learning Purposes**:\n   - If you\u2019re studying and using copied code to analyze or modify it, that\u2019s a great way to learn. Just ensure you understand how it works.\n\n---\n\n### When It\u2019s Not OK:\n1. **Blind Copying**:\n   - Copying code without understanding it defeats the purpose of competitive programming, which is to improve your problem-solving and coding skills.\n\n2. **Plagiarism**:\n   - In contests with strict rules, copying others\u2019 solutions or code from the internet without permission can lead to disqualification or penalties.\n\n3. **Missing the Point**:\n   - If you rely too heavily on copied code, you might miss opportunities to develop your own problem-solving strategies and coding techniques.\n\n4. **Unfamiliar Code**:\n   - Using code you don\u2019t understand can introduce bugs or inefficiencies that are hard to debug under time pressure.\n\n---\n\n### Best Practices:\n- **Understand the Code**: Only use copied code if you know how it works and can modify it if needed.\n- **Use Trusted Sources**: Copy from reliable sources like well-documented libraries or your own codebase.\n- **Attribute When Necessary**: If you\u2019re using someone else\u2019s code (e.g., in a blog or open-source project), give credit where it\u2019s due.\n- **Practice Implementing Algorithms**: Try to implement algorithms from scratch during practice to build your skills.\n\nUltimately, copying code is a tool, and like any tool, it\u2019s about how you use it. Use it wisely to enhance your efficiency without compromising your learning and growth.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
